Preheat the #oven{} to 200°C. Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves} (or use a #garlic press{}). Drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1%400g can} in a #sieve{}. Pop half the chickpeas in a #bowl{} and roughly mash with back of a #fork{} until broken up. Set aside for later.

Heat a #frying pan{} on high heat (no oil). When hot, add the @lamb mince{200%g} and cook until browned, ~{4-5%minutes}. Use a #wooden spoon{} to break it up as it cooks. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> The mince is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Reduce to medium heat and add the @shawarma spice mix{1%tsp}, garlic and @tomato puree{30%g}. Stir and cook for ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add the @water{100%ml}, to the pan with the lamb along with the whole and mashed chickpeas and @beef stock powder{1}. Mix to combine, bring to the boil and allow to simmer until thickened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Pop the @plain naans{2} on a #baking tray{} and top each with equal servings of lamb mix. Bake in the oven for ~{5-6%minutes}.

Meanwhile, pop the @red wine vinegar{12%ml}, @olive oil{1%tbsp} and @sugar{1/2%tsp} into a bowl. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and mix together. Trim the root from the @baby gem lettuce{1}. Add the baby gem to the bowl with the dressing and toss together.

Once the lamb flatbread is out the oven, serve on plates, drizzle over the @low fat natural yoghurt{75%g} and sprinkle over the @za'atar{1}. Serve with the baby gem salad on the side. Enjoy!